Title:
PoisonX: Terminating Protected Windows Processes via BYOVD

Type:
Blog Post (with linked GitHub Tool)

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This write-up presents PoisonX, a research tool that demonstrates Bring Your Own Vulnerable Driver (BYOVD) to terminate arbitrary Windows processes, including Protected Process (PP) and Protected Process Light (PPL) targets such as EDR/AV services.  
- It abuses a Microsoft-signed kernel driver that exposes a vulnerable IOCTL interface, allowing the driver to be loaded under Windows Code Integrity and then used as a kernel-level “kill” primitive.  
- The user-mode controller installs/uninstalls the driver via the Service Control Manager, communicates with it using DeviceIoControl, and can enumerate processes along with their PP/PPL protection level and signer info.  
- The tool auto-deploys by extracting one of multiple embedded driver variants and issuing an IOCTL (0x22E010) to terminate a specified PID.  
- It’s useful for red teams and security researchers to validate endpoint resilience against BYOVD-based defense evasion, and for blue teams to understand detection points around driver loading and suspicious IOCTL usage.  
- The key takeaway is that trusted, signed-but-vulnerable drivers can bypass user-mode protections and undermine PPL-based security controls.

Technical Focus:
- BYOVD (Bring Your Own Vulnerable Driver) abuse
- Windows PP/PPL process protection bypass via kernel primitives
- Vulnerable IOCTL interfaces and DeviceIoControl user↔kernel communication
- Microsoft-signed driver trust chain / Windows Code Integrity implications
- Driver installation and lifecycle via Service Control Manager (SCM)
- Process enumeration with protection level and signer attribution

Use Cases:
- Terminate EDR/AV PPL services during controlled red-team testing
- Validate defensive controls: driver blocklists, driver-load telemetry, IOCTL monitoring
- Research PP/PPL behavior and signer/protection-level mapping across processes
- Build detections for suspicious kernel driver service creation and device GUID access
- Reproduce and study real-world BYOVD tradecraft used by ransomware/malware

Keywords:
BYOVD, vulnerable driver, Microsoft-signed driver, Windows Hardware Compatibility Publisher, IOCTL, DeviceIoControl, kernel-mode, SCM, Service Control Manager, PP, Protected Process, PPL, Protected Process Light, SeDebugPrivilege, EDR bypass, process termination, driver blocklist, Code Integrity, device interface GUID, CrowdStrike Falcon